l context, Contested Embrace illuminates the political and bureaucratic construction of ethno-national populations beyond the territorial boundary of the state. Through a comparative analysis of transborder membership politics in the colonial, Cold War, and post-Cold War periods, the book shows how the configuration of geopolitics, bureaucratic techniques, and actors' agency shapes the making, unmaking, and remaking of transborder ties. Kim demonstrates that being a "homeland" state or a member of the "transborder nation" is a precarious, arduous, and revocable political achievement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aKorean diasporaxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th century. 0aKorean diasporaxPolitical aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aKoreansxHistoryx20th centuryxChina. 0aKoreansxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aKoreanszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aKoreanszJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aTransnationalismxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxKorea. 0aTransnationalismxPolitical aspectszKoreaxHistoryy20th century. 4aChina. 4aCold War. 4aJapan. 4aKorea. 4acolonial migration. 4adiaspora/homeland. 4anationalism/transnationalism. 4astate's symbolic power. 4atransborder membership politics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804799614zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799614423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799614.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles